		<title>Raja Koduri’s OXMIQ Raises $35M To License AI Chips Instead Of Building</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/raja-koduri-oxmiq-raises-35m-license-ai-chips/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 02 Jul 2026 13:55:11 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[AI]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Startup]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[AI hardware]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[artificial intelligence]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[GPU]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Intel Capital]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[MediaTek]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[OXMIQ Labs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Samsung]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=203286</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>To build a custom artificial intelligence (AI) hardware, a tech company would need massive bank accounts and years of development. Most tech companies simply cannot afford both to remain competitive</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/raja-koduri-oxmiq-raises-35m-license-ai-chips/" data-wpel-link="internal">Raja Koduri’s OXMIQ Raises $35M To License AI Chips Instead Of Building</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To build a custom artificial intelligence (AI) hardware, a tech company would need massive bank accounts and years of development. Most tech companies simply cannot afford both to remain competitive in the rapidly growing AI space. Silicon veteran </span><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/raja-koduri-3a51611" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Raja Koduri</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> wants to break this barrier. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">His startup, OXMIQ Labs, just </span><a href="https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20260701241910/en/OXMIQ-Raises-%2435-Million-to-Scale-OxCore-Architecture" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">closed</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> a $35 million Series A funding round. As OXMIQ raises $35 million, the company’s total funding has hit $60 million. Instead of building physical chips, OXMIQ plans to license its innovative GPU architecture. </span></p>
<div id="attachment_203290" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203290" class="size-large wp-image-203290" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/60Million-1024x576.jpg" alt="A corporate graphic by OXMIQ from July 2026 announcing a total of $60 Million raised, featuring prominent logos of high-profile backing investors." width="1024" height="576" /><p id="caption-attachment-203290" class="wp-caption-text">$60 Million Total Funding Announcement. Image Credit: OXMIQ</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Co-led by Fundomo and the Samsung Catalyst Fund, the round also drew support from major industry heavyweights like MediaTek and Intel Capital. OXMIQ targets the massive bottleneck in global AI infrastructure. </span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Power of Open Silicon Architecture</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The traditional chip industry relies heavily on centralized control and proprietary ecosystems. </span><a href="https://oxmiq.ai/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">OXMIQ Labs</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> aims to disrupt this paradigm with an open approach. Legendary chip architect and Tenstorrent CEO Jim Keller has officially joined the company’s board of directors. </span></p>
<div id="attachment_203289" style="width: 770px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203289" class="size-full wp-image-203289" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Jim-Keller-and.jpg" alt="A medium shot of legendary microprocessor engineer Jim Keller and OXMIQ founder Raja Koduri standing side-by-side at a tech event." width="760" height="489" /><p id="caption-attachment-203289" class="wp-caption-text">Jim Keller and Raja Koduri. Image Credit: Business Insider</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Keller emphasizes that an open GPU foundation is vital to dismantle the artificial boundaries restricting modern AI innovation. Incumbent tech giants currently dominate the computing infrastructure market. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This concentration limits choices for smaller developers and system builders. OXMIQ’s capital-efficient business model allows clients to own their computing roadmaps. By focusing exclusively on architectural IP, the startup generates steady revenue through early customer engagements. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Meanwhile, it avoids the astronomical manufacturing expenses that frequently drain hardware startups. This open ecosystem allows smaller design teams to compete globally.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More News: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/together-ai-raises-800m-series-c-open-source-valuation/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>Together AI Raises $800M to Scale Cheaper Open-Source Models</i></b></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Inside the OxCore and OxQuilt Engines</span></h2>
<div id="attachment_203288" style="width: 810px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203288" class="size-full wp-image-203288" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/1768575328113.jpeg" alt="An isometric architectural breakdown diagram demonstrating how the OxCore GPU IP scales into an Inference SoC and a massive Training POD using the OxQuilt SoC Builder." width="800" height="450" /><p id="caption-attachment-203288" class="wp-caption-text">OxQuilt SoC Builder Architecture: Image Credit OXMIQ</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">At the heart of the company’s technology stack sits OxCore. This scalable, licensable GPU core combines three vital compute engines into a single system. It integrates a CUDA-compatible GPU engine, a tensor processing engine, and a CPU orchestration engine. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This design unifies operations that traditionally require three separate physical chips. OxCore optimizes near-memory computing to reduce data movement and slash energy consumption. OXMIQ pairs this core with OxQuilt, a flexible chiplet integration architecture. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Traditional AI chip designs lock developers into a specific manufacturing foundry or memory type. OxQuilt bypasses this limitation entirely. It adapts to any supply chain, letting customers mix different logic process nodes and advanced packaging options.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Seamless Software Portability</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Hardware is only as good as the software running on top of it. OXMIQ tackles this problem with OxPython, a dedicated software layer designed for zero-friction deployment. OxPython allows developers to run existing CUDA and PyTorch code directly on OxCore hardware. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Crucially, this requires absolutely zero code modifications. Developers retain full software portability across diverse platforms without losing performance. This software-first mindset guarantees immediate compatibility with newly released AI models. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">OXMIQ is currently demonstrating its architecture live on FPGA setups. The company is actively collaborating with semiconductor firms, robotics innovators, and AI system builders eager to control their hardware future.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Demand for AI processing tokens is currently outpacing physical data center growth. By offering an intellectual property (IP) licensing model, the startup enables companies to design custom AI silicon without launching cost-prohibitive full chip development programs.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More News: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/leapxpert-raises-180m-to-unlock-insights-from-work-chats/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>LeapXpert Raises $180M to Unlock Insights From Work Chats</i></b></a></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/raja-koduri-oxmiq-raises-35m-license-ai-chips/" data-wpel-link="internal">Raja Koduri’s OXMIQ Raises $35M To License AI Chips Instead Of Building</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
